SIMPLE: ingraft
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ingraft
<hw>In*graft"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ingrafted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ingrafting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also
<ets>engraft</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To insert, as a scion of one tree, shrub, or plant
in another for propagation; <as>as, to <ex>ingraft</ex> a peach scion on
a plum tree</as>;</def> <mark>[figuratively]</mark>, <def>to insert or
introduce in such a way as to make a part of something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This fellow would <qex>ingraft</qex> a foreign name⟦br⟧
Upon our stock.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A custom . . . <qex>ingrafted</qex> into the monarchy of Rome.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subject to the process of grafting; to furnish
with grafts or scions; to graft; <as>as, to <ex>ingraft</ex> a
tree</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ingrafter</ent>⟦br⟧
